Gemini said
Moving beyond a simple app launcher is when Rofi really starts to shine. Since Rofi can read from stdin, you can pipe virtually any text into it and act on the selection.

To turn Rofi into a searchable "Cheat Sheet" or "Notes Overlay," you can use Script Mode or a simple one-liner script.

Method 1: The "Quick & Dirty" One-Liner
If you have a text file (e.g., ~/notes/hotkeys.txt) where each line is a note or a keybinding, you can pipe it directly into Rofi.

Update your Hyprland bind to this:

Bash
bind = $mainMod, N, exec, cat ~/path/to/notes.txt | rofi -dmenu -i -p "Notes"
-dmenu: Tells Rofi to act as a generic menu for the piped text.

-i: Makes the search case-insensitive.

-p: Sets a custom prompt label.

Method 2: The "Interactive Note-Taker" (Recommended)
If you want to be able to view a note and then actually do something with it (like copy it to your clipboard), you’ll want a small script.

Create a file named rofi-notes.sh:

Bash
#!/bin/bash

# Path to your notes file
NOTES_FILE="$HOME/Documents/cheat_sheet.txt"

# 1. Get the selection from Rofi
# 2. Use 'xclip' or 'wl-copy' (for Wayland) to put it in clipboard
selected=$(cat "$NOTES_FILE" | rofi -dmenu -i -p "Reference:")

if [ -n "$selected" ]; then
    echo "$selected" | wl-copy
    notify-send "Copied to clipboard" "$selected"
fi
Make it executable: chmod +x rofi-notes.sh.

Bind it in Hyprland:

Bash
bind = $mainMod, N, exec, /path/to/rofi-notes.sh
Method 3: Organized "Key-Value" Lookups
If your notes are structured as Topic: Detail, you can use awk to show the topic but copy the detail. However, for a simple overlay, Rofi’s built-in script mode is the cleanest way to integrate with your existing config.

You can add this to your config.rasi:

Code snippet
configuration {
    modi: "drun,run,notes:/path/to/rofi-notes.sh";
}
Then you can toggle between "Apps" and "Notes" using Ctrl+Tab inside the Rofi window.

Pro-Tip: Rofi-Beats / Rofi-RBW
Since you are on Wayland/Hyprland, you might eventually find that the standard rofi (X11) has some flickering or positioning issues. Most Hyprland users prefer rofi-wayland or wofi. The commands above work exactly the same for rofi-wayland.

