Gemini said
Using Neovim for this is a fantastic idea because it handles Markdown perfectly, keeps you in the terminal workflow, and allows you to actually edit the notes if you spot a typo.

Since you're on Hyprland, the trick is to launch your terminal emulator (like kitty, alacritty, or foot) in a floating window specifically for this "overlay" feel.

Method: The Rofi-to-Neovim Pipeline
This workflow uses Rofi to search your filenames and then opens the selection in a floating Neovim instance.

1. The Script (~/bin/rofi-md-notes.sh)
Create this script to list your .md files and launch them:

Bash
#!/bin/bash

# Directory where your markdown notes live
NOTES_DIR="$HOME/Documents/notes"

# 1. Get the filename via Rofi
# -printf "%P\n" strips the full path from the view
selection=$(find "$NOTES_DIR" -name "*.md" -printf "%P\n" | rofi -dmenu -i -p "Search Notes:")

# 2. If a selection was made, open it in a floating terminal
if [ -n "$selection" ]; then
    # Change 'kitty' to your terminal of choice
    hyprctl dispatch exec "[float; size 60% 70%; center] kitty nvim '$NOTES_DIR/$selection'"
fi
2. Hyprland Configuration
Add this to your hyprland.conf:

Bash
bind = $mainMod, N, exec, ~/bin/rofi-md-notes.sh
Why this works well:
Hyprland Window Rules: By using [float; size 60% 70%; center], you don't have to permanently mess with your layout. The note pops up as a true "overlay" and disappears once you :q out of Neovim.

Markdown Rendering: If you have a Neovim plugin like render-markdown.nvim or headlines.nvim, your notes will look beautiful and structured, unlike a raw text dump in Rofi.

Searchability: Rofi handles the "fuzzy finding" of the file titles, while Neovim handles the "content" interaction.

Pro-Level Tip: Searching Inside the Files
If you want to search the content of the notes (not just the filenames), replace the find command in the script with grep or rg (ripgrep):

Bash
# This shows the filename AND the line containing your search term
selection=$(rg --no-heading --column --smart-case "" "$NOTES_DIR" | rofi -dmenu -i -p "Find Text:")

# Then extract just the filename and line number to open Neovim at the right spot
file=$(echo "$selection" | cut -d: -f1)
line=$(echo "$selection" | cut -d: -f2)

if [ -n "$file" ]; then
    hyprctl dispatch exec "[float; size 60% 70%] kitty nvim +$line '$file'"
fi
